I'll start by executing the file_operations_reader tool to read the input data as the first step in the pipeline.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll now execute the data_processing_filter tool to filter the data we read in the previous step. Since we're working with JSON data, I'll use default filtering options.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "options": {
    "format": "json",
    "filter_type": "basic"
  }
}
</tool_call>

I'll now execute the data_processing_transformer tool to transform our filtered JSON data. Since we're working with JSON throughout the pipeline, I'll keep the same input and output format.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now I'll proceed with the final validation step using the data_processing_validator tool. I'll use a basic JSON schema validation as the default option.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
